            <h1>Exploratory Data Analysis</h1>

            <section>
                <h2>1. Dataset Overview</h2>
                <p>
                    The data were collected through API access from two primary sources. From Federal Reserve
                    Economic Data (FRED), we obtained the unemployment rate, inflation rate, federal funds
                    interest rate, and the oil data. From Yahoo Finance, we collected financial
                    market indicators including the S&P 500 index, the VIX volatility index, and gold prices.
                </p>

                <p>
                    The analysis primarily uses data beginning in 1968 for unemployment, inflation, interest
                    rates, and the S&P 500 index. However, VIX, gold price and oil data are only available starting
                    from 1990. As a result, analyses involving these three variables are restricted to the period
                    from 1990 onward.
                </p>
            </section>

            <section>
                <h2>2. Data Cleaning and Preparation</h2>

                <div style="overflow-x: auto;">
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Indicator</th>
                                <th>Description</th>
                                <th>Frequency</th>
                                <th>Range</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Unemployment</td>
                                <td>the unemployment rate (seasonally adjusted)</td>
                                <td>monthly</td>
                                <td>0 - 15</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Inflation</td>
                                <td>the inflation rate</td>
                                <td>annually</td>
                                <td>-3 - 15</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Interest rates</td>
                                <td>the federal funds rate (monthly average)</td>
                                <td>monthly</td>
                                <td>0 - 20</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Oil prices</td>
                                <td>the price of West Texas Intermediate crude oil (monthly average)</td>
                                <td>daily</td>
                                <td>50 - 130</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>SP500</td>
                                <td>the S&P 500 index (monthly close)</td>
                                <td>daily</td>
                                <td>100 - 8000</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>VIX</td>
                                <td>the CBOE Volatility Index (daily close, monthly average)</td>
                                <td>daily</td>
                                <td>0 - 60</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Gold</td>
                                <td>the price of gold (monthly close)</td>
                                <td>monthly</td>
                                <td>250 - 6000</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>

                <p style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">
                    As shown in the table, the given data was recorded in different frequencies, so all indicators were
                    converted to a standard monthly frequency to allow for direct comparison. The data was then merged
                    with the recession indicator dataframe. As data for VIX and Gold are only available starting from
                    1990, the dataset was split into two segments: one covering 1968-2026 (Unemployment, Inflation,
                    Interest rates, and S&P 500) and another covering 1990-2026 (VIX, Gold, and Oil).
                </p>

                <p>
                    Furthermore, the indicators have completely different value ranges (e.g., S&P 500 in thousands vs.
                    Interest rates in small percentages). To plot and compare them effectively, two different scaling
                    techniques were applied throughout the analysis: <b>Min-Max Normalization</b> and <b>Z-score
                        Standardization</b>.
                </p>

                <details class="zscore-highlight" style="cursor: pointer; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
                    <summary style="font-weight: bold; color: var(--link-color);">Min-Max Normalization</summary>
                    <div style="margin-top: 10px; font-size: 0.95rem; cursor: auto;">
                        <p><b>Where and Why:</b> Used in Section 3 (Visualization Analysis) to scale all indicators
                            between 0 and 1. This allows us to plot long-term trends of vastly different indicators
                            (like S&P 500 and Unemployment) on the same graph to see their overall directional movements
                            over decades.</p>
                        <p style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;"><b>Formula:</b>
                            <code>X_norm = (X - X_min) / (X_max - X_min)</code>
                        </p>
                        <ul style="margin-bottom: 0;">
                            <li><b>X</b>: The original data value</li>
                            <li><b>X_min</b>: The minimum value of the indicator</li>
                            <li><b>X_max</b>: The maximum value of the indicator</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </details>

                <details class="zscore-highlight" style="cursor: pointer; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
                    <summary style="font-weight: bold; color: var(--link-color);">Z-score Standardization</summary>
                    <div style="margin-top: 10px; font-size: 0.95rem; cursor: auto;">
                        <p><b>Where and Why:</b> Used in Section 3.1 (Average Indicator Trajectory) to evaluate how much
                            each indicator deviates from its historical average in the months leading up to a recession.
                            Because it centers the data around 0 and scales by variance, we can directly compare the
                            relative "spike" or "drop" intensities (e.g., measuring market fear vs. interest rate hikes)
                            in standard deviation units.</p>
                        <p style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;"><b>Formula:</b> <code>Z = (X - μ) / σ</code></p>
                        <ul style="margin-bottom: 0;">
                            <li><b>X</b>: The original data value</li>
                            <li><b>μ</b>: The mean (average) of the indicator</li>
                            <li><b>σ</b>: The standard deviation (spread) of the indicator</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </details>

            </section>


